[This report is a continuation of the 13 Oct 2011 ProMED-mail post
(archive 20111013.3064), with more details and information about the
development of new regulations. The fatal case [7 year old girl] is
the same case as reported before.

Maintaining a high degree of rabies immunity in a large, ever-changing
un-owned population of street dogs is difficult. A
vaccination/neutering program may help to stabilize the population and
maintain a higher level of herd immunity. More frequent vaccination
campaigns may be necessary in Cochabamba department. One hopes that
the new ordinances in Cochabamba will also be helpful but these will
require public education and enforcement to be effective.

In the past 6 months, rabies has been a significant problem in other
departments in Bolivia as well. Canine rabies cases have also been
reported in Oruro, La Paz, and Santa Cruz departments this year
(2011).

A map of the Departments of Bolivia can be accessed at
http://www.boliviabella.com/images/bolivia_facts_maps_provinces.gif.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of
Cochabamba can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1iuQ. - Mod.TY]
